# Agent Conventions

Before architectural or cross-cutting changes, read the project's agent docs:

1. `AGENTS.md` (primary)
2. `claude.md` at repo root, if present
3. `agents.md` at repo root, if present

Also scan `.agents/` for any additional convention files. Use those docs for bounded-context ownership, import boundaries, terrain/foot sync, security, and performance pitfalls. Do not restate them here — read the source files.

Project skills (read when the domain matches): `.cursor/skills/prefab-editor/SKILL.md`, `.cursor/skills/ship-flight/SKILL.md`, `.cursor/skills/prd/SKILL.md`.

## Performance — first-class requirement

ClaudeCitizen is a **real-time web game** (TypeScript + Three.js/WebGL) backed by an authoritative, horizontally scalable Rust cell simulation. Performance is not a polish pass — it is a **core product constraint**. A Star Citizen–scale world on the web fails instantly if the main thread stalls, draw calls explode, or sync work scales with player count.

**Treat every change as a frame-budget decision.** Aim for sustained interactive framerate; profile when unsure; prefer bounded, incremental work over "do it all now" loops.

### When performance matters (always)

- Game loop, render path, terrain/LOD, vegetation, ship/station loading
- UI that re-renders during play (HUD, menus, editor panels)
- Per-frame or per-tick simulation (`world/`, `flight/`, `player/`, `npc/`)
- Asset size, mesh complexity, texture resolution, GLB/GLTF loads
- Workers, caching, and anything that can block the main thread
- Backend: tick rate, interest fan-out, payload size, DB hot paths

### Client — TypeScript + Three.js

- **Main thread is sacred.** Heavy work belongs in Web Workers (`planet_tile_worker.js`), async loads, or spread across frames — never unbounded sync loops on the hot path.
- **Respect existing budgets.** Per-frame tile/vegetation build caps, LOD selection, and quality presets (`?quality=performance|balanced|high`) exist because unbounded work freezes the game at 0 FPS.
- **UI stays out of the render loop.** UI updates on state/events; avoid new object/array allocations every frame in shared paths.
- **Three.js discipline.** Reuse geometries/materials; instancing where possible; frustum/distance culling; minimize scene graph churn and `dispose()` leaks.
- **Measure.** Use the in-game FPS counter and quality presets when validating changes; see AGENTS.md "Terrain mesh vs foot placement" for terrain-specific traps.

### Backend — Rust authoritative cells

- **Server tick is a budget too.** Simulation, interest management, and broadcasts must scale with concurrent players — design for O(players-in-range), not O(world).
- **WebTransport payloads stay compact.** Protobuf intents use datagrams; reliable streams carry control and reconciliation. Never ship unfiltered world state every tick.
- **Authority without blocking.** Cell ticks must not wait on synchronous database or network work. Checkpoint and route outside the hot path.
- **Client sends intents, cells decide outcomes.** Native Rapier owns collision and outcomes; browser prediction must use the shared Rust/WASM core.
- **One owner per cell.** Redis leases route work; PostgreSQL epochs fence stale owners. Never introduce a dual-backend or WebSocket fallback.

## When to read

- Adding features or changing module boundaries
- Touching terrain mesh, foot placement, or LOD
- Working with assets, builds, secrets, or protected paths
- Any change that affects architecture or cross-layer dependencies
- Anything on the main thread, in the frame loop, or on a future realtime server path

## Quick triggers

- New feature → which bounded context owns it? (`world/`, `flight/`, `player/`, `npc/`, `render/`)
- Friendly station NPCs / waypoint routes / population definitions → `src/npc/` plus AGENTS.md "Friendly station NPCs"
- Terrain / character grounding → see AGENTS.md "Terrain mesh vs foot placement"
- Terrain/veg **code** edits (placement, mesh layout, multipliers, buffers, asset-loading path) → bump `TERRAIN_CACHE_VERSION` / `VEGETATION_CACHE_VERSION` in `src/cache/cache_keys.ts`; see AGENTS.md "Terrain & vegetation disk cache invalidation" and `.cursor/rules/terrain-cache.mdc`. Planet Authoring JSON knobs (including vegetation `assetUrls`) invalidate automatically — no bump.
- Assets / build / secrets → see AGENTS.md "Security"
- Editor / scene / prefab / GLB node operations → `.cursor/rules/prefab-editor.mdc` and AGENTS.md "Editor (Electron desktop)"
- Ship flight / mass / thrust / IFCS / dual-reticle / Preview Ship flight → `.cursor/rules/ship-flight.mdc`, `.cursor/skills/ship-flight/SKILL.md`, and AGENTS.md "Ship flight"
- PRD / phased handoff pack under `prds/` → `.cursor/skills/prd/SKILL.md` (mirror `prds/system-map/`)
- Slow or stuttery? → check frame budgets, LOD, React re-renders, and sync work before adding features

## Key reminders

- Domain logic lives in `world/`, `flight/`, `player/`, `npc/` — not in `render/` or `app.js`
- Terrain mesh and foot placement must share the uniform per-LOD band-limited grid; preserve `renderableGridSampleSpacingMeters()` ownership, mixed-LOD edge stitching, two-sided fallback skirts, pinned L0 fallback coverage, and the cached downhill river graph
- Never commit or relocate `protected/` assets
- No unit tests in this project
- User owns interactive QA. Agents may run non-interactive build and static validation (`cargo check`, `cargo build`, `cargo clippy`, `npm run build`, `npm run typecheck`, and `npm run lint`) when useful. Do not run tests, browser QA, screenshot checks, or dev-server validation unless explicitly asked. At the end of a multi-file feature or spike, run `npm run lint` and fix errors (and trivial warnings in touched files when practical). If relevant validation is skipped, say so in the handoff. For explicit commit requests, run `npm run typecheck` and `npm run lint` first unless told not to.
- **SQLx:** append migrations in `backend/migrations/`; `npm run backend:migrate` applies committed migrations. Do not introduce another ORM or migration system.
- Do not start dev servers. The editor is a standalone Electron application and does not use Vite serving. Do not run `npm run dev:web`, `npm run dev:server`, `npm run start:dev`, `vite`, `tsx watch`, or similar long-running local servers unless explicitly asked. If server context is needed, check existing ports/processes or ask first.
- `npm run dev:server` is the Watchexec rebuild/restart loop; `npm run start:server` runs the Rust backend once. Agents still must not start either without explicit authorization.
- **If it can freeze the tab or tank server tick rate, fix or bound it before shipping**
